          "body": "The catalogue of damaging neighbors (vv. 18-20) names three: the false witness (a club and sword and sharp arrow — weapons of assault), the faithless man in crisis (a broken tooth and unsteady foot — structural failures that betray), and the person who sings cheerful songs to a troubled heart (vinegar on a wound — well-intentioned harm). The catalogue is not random; it moves from deliberate harm (false witness) to negligent harm (the faithless man) to accidental harm (the tone-deaf comforter). Against that backdrop, verses 21-22 land with full force: if your enemy is hungry, feed him; if he is thirsty, give him water. The logic of 'burning coals heaped on his head' has generated sustained interpretive debate — it most likely refers to the Egyptian ritual of carrying coals on the head as a sign of penitence, which would mean that enemy-feeding produces the enemy's shame and potential repentance (so Duane Garrett, *Proverbs*, NAC). The New Testament citation in Romans 12:20 places the proverb within a framework of overcoming evil with good rather than vengeance. Either reading serves the same ethical end: the Lord's reward underwrites what natural self-interest cannot motivate. Verse 26 closes with the chapter's sharpest social warning: the righteous man who yields to the wicked is a muddied spring, a polluted well. Righteousness is not a private achievement — it is the water source the whole community drinks from, and moral capitulation poisons the commons."
