        "title": "God conceals, kings investigate — the epistemology of authority",
        "range": "25:1-7",
        "excerpt": "It is the glory of God to conceal a matter, but the glory of kings is to search out a matter.",
        "body": "Verse 2 is one of the most theologically compressed sentences in Proverbs. Its two halves do not set God and kings in competition — they assign each a distinctive excellence. God's glory (*kavod*) is concealment (*satar*): mystery, hiddenness, the withholding of what only He knows. This is the theological anchor of Deuteronomy 29:29 ('The secret things belong to the LORD our God') and of Isaiah 45:15 ('Truly You are a God who hides Himself'). The inaccessibility of God is not a defect but a perfection — it belongs to His incomprehensibility, what classical theologians call the *deus absconditus*.\n\nThe king's glory is the complementary opposite: to search out (*chaqar*), to investigate, to probe. The royal calling is epistemic — the king is obligated to know, to adjudicate, to pursue what is hidden in human affairs. This is the mandate behind the legal institution in Deuteronomy 17:8-11 (the king's court as the court of final appeal) and the wisdom Solomon himself exercised in 1 Kings 3:16-28. The chapter opens by legitimating investigative royal authority as a God-assigned vocation.\n\nVerse 3 immediately relativizes that authority. The king's heart is unsearchable — as high as the heavens, as deep as the earth. The courtier who aspires to know the king's mind, to game his intentions, or to predict his decisions is warned: you cannot get there from here. This epistemological humility governs the practical counsel of verses 6-7. Do not push your way to the elevated seat; wait to be invited. The reason is not merely social decorum — it is that the king's preferences are inaccessible, and presuming to know them (or to deserve his favor) is a form of arrogance about which you have no grounds.\n\nThe silver-refining analogy of verses 4-5 addresses the court from a different angle. The righteous advisor's task is removal of the wicked, not promotion of himself. Just as the metalsmith cannot produce a vessel until dross is removed, the king cannot produce a righteous kingdom until corrupt counsel is named and expelled. This is the prophetic function operating within the court — Nathan before David (2 Samuel 12), Elijah before Ahab (1 Kings 21). The wise courtier is not the one who flatters the king but the one who identifies what corrupts him.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kavod* (glory, vv. 2, 27) — literally 'heaviness,' the weightiness that commands respect. *Chaqar* (search out, v. 2) and *cheqer* (its noun, v. 3) — the same root used for Job's probing of divine wisdom in Job 11:7. *Hagah* (remove, vv. 4-5) — more commonly 'to meditate' (Psalm 1:2), but here carries the sense of removing by sifting or winnowing. The silver-refining metaphor echoes Psalm 12:6 and Isaiah 48:10."
