        "number": 3,
        "title": "Honey, neighbors, and the discipline of enough",
        "range": "25:16-17",
        "excerpt": "Have you found honey? Eat only what you need, that you not have it in excess and vomit it.",
        "body": "Verses 16-17 are the chapter's restraint-proverbs in miniature, and they are thematically paired. The honey proverb addresses appetite for what is genuinely good; the visitation proverb addresses appetite for what is genuinely pleasant (a neighbor's company). In both cases the proverb does not condemn the thing itself — honey is good; neighborly friendship is valuable — but locates the corruption in excess. This is not Stoic asceticism; it is covenant wisdom. The creation is good (Genesis 1:31), its pleasures are gifts (Ecclesiastes 2:24-25; 1 Timothy 4:4), and the right response to good things is moderation, not abstinence.\n\nThe literary structure of these two verses mirrors the book's larger honey-frame: the invitation to eat honey in Proverbs 24:13 ('Eat honey, my son, for it is good') is now qualified by Proverbs 25:16 (eat only what you need) and Proverbs 25:27 (too much honey is not good). Proverbs does not oscillate on honey — it teaches a consistent appetite-theology: taste it, enjoy it, stop before excess converts gift into punishment. The vomiting image in verse 16 is deliberately visceral; the text does not permit a sanitized reading of what overindulgence produces.\n\nThe neighbor-visitation proverb (v. 17) applies the same logic relationally. The Hebrew *yaqar* (make rare) is the verb of preciousness — what is rare is valuable; what is commonplace loses its value. Showing up too often at a neighbor's house converts the value of your presence into a burden. The proverb is not cynical about friendship; it is realistic about human appetite for novelty and solitude. Proverbs 27:10 ('Do not forsake your friend or your father's friend') requires neighborly loyalty; Proverbs 25:17 requires it to breathe. Both are necessary.\n\nTogether these two proverbs make a case for what might be called the wisdom of *less*: less honey, less presence, less self-promotion (v. 27), less speech (the soft tongue of v. 15 is more powerful than the loud one). The chapter's master-virtue of restraint is not negative asceticism but the positive discipline of the person who has learned that enough is more than too much."
